					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">But then DOS games could afford a bigger sliding window/update region because 8086 CPUs had 16-bit machine words, unlike the 8-bit machine words of 6502 CPUs. An 8086 program thus didn't need to do a 2-machine-word comparison with carry to determine when something was going in or out of the sliding window.
<br />
<br />Super Bat Puncher persists while a map segment is loaded on the screen. Anything offscreen persists in a stopped state.</div>

